season_overview.summary: Through Week 9 the league has settled into a clear top tier and a crowded middle. Kraft Montgomery Cheese (8-2) and SnydeRemarks (7-3) have the best records; a four-team cluster at 6-4 (Hangin' With Mr. Cooper, Forte Inch Johnson, The Philly Special, 5WRsAllowedOnRostersNextYear) occupies the next rung. The season has been defined by frequent single-player outliers (explosive RB/WR/TE games and occasional QB blowups), consequential bench decisions (many matchups swung by 20+ point bench scores left unused), and several D/ST and kicker performances that created unexpected point swings.
notable_patterns: High variance weeks: many blowouts (multiple 140+ team totals) and frequent single-digit games; outcomes often decided by a single roster decision.

Frequent large bench swings: managers repeatedly left 20+ point performances unused (examples across weeks: Daniel Jones, Trevor Lawrence, C.J. Stroud, Bijan Robinson, Rico Dowdle, Jordan Love, Justin Fields).

D/ST and kickers have been more impactful than typical—several weeks featured D/STs or kickers producing double-digit, game-deciding outputs (Vikings D/ST 32, Browns D/ST 24, Saints D/ST 18, multiple kickers 17+).
Some teams show consistent high outputs (SnydeRemarks, Kraft) while others are boom-or-bust with big wins offset by sudden collapses (THE Derbaum, Jake Butt Stuff).

teams.team: If Ur Not First You're Last
teams.trend: Explosive WR weeks (Nabers, Odunze) but streaky Mahomes/Tua performance variation and occasional zero WR weeks have produced swings.
High variance: occasional huge wins (Derrick Henry/Deebo early) but many low-output weeks; roster has shown both big bench gems and glaring misses.

notes: Standings use Week 9 results. Where available, season points-for/against were taken from latest weekly data.
Tie-breakers among 6-4 teams were resolved by Points For when head-to-head data was unavailable; the four teams at 6-4 are all competing for seeds 3–6 and separation is narrow.

playoff_projection_top_6.method: Top 6 by record, tie-broken by head-to-head where available then Points For (PF)
bubble_notes: Four teams at 6-4 made the projected field; small changes in the remaining weeks (single wins or a swing in Points For) can reshuffle seeds.
Teams with high PF among the 6-4 group (Hangin' and Forte) have an edge for seeding if head-to-head does not separate them.

common_themes: Bench management has been the largest consistent factor separating winners from losers; multiple seasons' worth of 'left on bench' 20+ point performances are documented league-wide.
D/ST and kicker volatility has produced outsized single-week value; managers who consider D/ST/kicker weekly matchups have gained clear advantages in individual weeks.

Some rosters are built for volatility (high-upside WR/TE stacks), while others have built stronger floors with consistent RB production — both approaches have achieved wins depending on how many single-game outliers hit in a given week.

team_examples.pattern: Highest ceiling team to date; regularly posts the highest weekly totals and benefits from star RB/QB weeks plus frequent WR breakouts.
Most consistent top seed: a mix of reliable RBs and opportunistic defensive/kicker weeks that turn close matchups in their favor.
Inconsistency driven by bench/inactive decisions and underperforming receivers some weeks; big QB weeks have not fully offset roster management issues.
Boom-or-bust: capable of domination when HB/RB/WR align, but numerous low weeks keep overall record below expectations.

repeat_overperformers.evidence: Multiple massive weeks (Week 1-ish and Week 3, Week 7, Week 9 range) where CMC produced 20+ points; consistently a top weekly scorer for his roster.
Several strong multi-week QB outputs (Weeks 1, 3, 9) adding consistent upside when healthy/in lineup.
Historic single-week outlier (43.3, Week 9) that produced the largest single-player positive swing recorded in the weekly summaries.
Multiple weeks with TE heavy scoring (33.3 Week 8) that have produced outsized TE contributions for his team.
Huge QB outlier in Week 9 (38.7) and other mobile-QB weeks that occasionally carry his team.

repeat_underperformers_or_busts.evidence: Recurring underperformance vs projection across multiple weeks (notable very low outputs Weeks 2–4), reducing expected floor for his roster.

teams_impacted: If Ur Not First You're Last
repeat_underperformers_or_busts.evidence: Several games with very low output relative to projection (e.g., Week 3, Week 4), creating big negative deltas.
High highs but also dramatic busts (e.g., Week 6 underperformance), demonstrating volatility.

bench_impact_examples: Daniel Jones (multiple weeks) and Trevor Lawrence (multiple weeks) produced top-20 QB outputs while frequently sitting on benches; same for C.J. Stroud and Jordan Love in several matchups.
Big bench RB outputs left unused (Rico Dowdle, Bijan Robinson bench 35.8 in Week 5) changed several matchup outcomes had they been started.

league_wide_insights.scoring_environment: Overall scoring is elevated some weeks (several 140+ team totals) but also sees deep troughs (sub-70 team totals). The environment favors managers who either capture the weekly outlier or maintain a high-floor roster.
upsets_and_close_games: Multiple close games decided by <5 points across the season (examples: Team Santangelo 125.44 vs Big Trouble 125.18 in Week 5; Xavier Marks the Spot 127.8 vs Team Jon 124.26 Week 4; Kraft 114.42 vs Jake Butt Stuff 107.7 Week 9).

Significant upsets occurred when teams with lower projections benefited from single-player explosions and opponent bench miscues (e.g., Hangin' With Mr. Cooper 157.26 over THE Derbaum 96.34, Week 9 (Brock Bowers' 43.3)).
league_wide_insights.bench_and_inactives_impact: Frequent — leaving Daniel Jones (29.48), Trevor Lawrence (26+), Jordan Love (28.3), C.J. Stroud (28.76), Bijan Robinson (35.8) and others on the bench recurs as the single largest behavioral impact across matchups.
league_wide_insights.defense_and_kicker_influence: Several weeks where D/ST or kickers provided 10+ points swung close outcomes (Vikings D/ST 32, Buccaneers D/ST 16, multiple kickers 17+). Managers starting favorable D/ST matchups gained outsized edges.

recurring_risky_behaviors: Benching high-scoring QBs or RBs who then post big numbers (multiple managers left Trevor Lawrence, Daniel Jones, Jordan Love on bench in separate weeks).
Failing to adjust for byes/inactives (example: CeeDee Lamb and Brock Purdy inactives left rosters thin in multiple weeks).
Holding volatile WRs/TEs as bench lottery tickets instead of starting them when projections favored a start (multiple Week-by-week examples).
recurring_smart_behaviors: Active use of streaming D/STs and targeting matchups — several managers earned wins via D/ST choices (Vikings D/ST 32; Browns D/ST 24; Steelers D/ST 16).
Targeting high-floor RBs and pairing with high-upside WRs has been an effective formula for top teams (examples: Kraft, Forte).
Occasional aggressive lineup changes (starting a mid-tier kicker/D/ST based on matchup) paid off heavily for some managers.
notable_owner_decisions: Hangin' With Mr. Cooper started Brock Bowers in Week 9 and received a historic return (43.3) — decisive and high-reward decision.
Multiple managers repeatedly left large bench scores on the pine (Daniel Jones, Trevor Lawrence, C.J. Stroud, Jordan Love, Bijan Robinson, Rico Dowdle), costing narrow matchups.
Several owners started defenses or kickers that massively outperformed (Saints D/ST 18, Jaguars D/ST 14, Cameron Dicker 17), demonstrating attention to matchup-based starts.

summary: Bench/inactive management will continue to be a primary determinant of weekly outcomes — the league's pattern suggests managing by matchups (especially for D/ST and K) and ensuring bench QBs/RBs/WRs are activated when projections are favorable.
Tie-breaker sensitivity: the playoff picture is tight for seeds 3–6; small PF swings or one more win/loss could flip seeds significantly.
Injury/bye scheduling (several teams have already burned through byes and IR lists) will influence lineup flexibility and the ability to absorb low-output weeks.
